  abstract = {The number partitioning problem, or how to choose up sides for a ball game, presents a fascinating paradox in computer science. Despite being classified as NP-complete, children around the world solve it daily when dividing into teams. This apparent contradiction highlights that not all instances of hard problems are actually hard to solve. The article explores how the success of playground algorithms suggests that the partitioning task is not always as intractable as the term "NP-complete" implies. Recent results using tools from physics, mathematics, and computer science reveal exactly where the hard problem instances hide. The number partitioning problem has applications beyond playground games, including dual-processor job scheduling and other resource-allocation tasks. The work demonstrates an easy-hard-easy phase transition where many problem instances remain trivial to solve even for large problem sizes, earning it the designation as "the easiest hard problem."},
