  abstract = {We introduce a simple erasure recovery algorithm for codes derived from cascades of sparse bipartite graphs and analyze the algorithm by analyzing a corresponding discrete-time random process. As a result of our analysis, we obtain a simple criterion involving the fractions of nodes of different degrees on both sides of the graph which is necessary and sufficient for the decoding process to finish successfully with high probability. By carefully designing these graphs we can construct for any given rate R and any given real number $ε$ a family of linear codes of rate R which can be encoded in time proportional to $łn(1/ε)$ times their block length $n$. Furthermore, a codeword can be recovered with high probability from a portion of its entries of length $(1+ε)Rn$ or more, and the recovery algorithm also runs in time proportional to $n łn(1/ε)$. These codes have exceedingly fast software implementations and should be useful for compensating for packet loss in internet traffic. Our algorithms have been implemented and work well in practice; various implementation issues are discussed.},
